        <h1>LeetCode 3531: Minimum Number of Increasing Subsequence to Be Removed (C++)</h1>

        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given an integer array nums. In one operation, you can remove a strictly increasing subsequence from the array. Return the minimum number of operations needed to make the array empty.
            </p>
            <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                Input: nums = [5,3,1,4,2]<br/>
                Output: 3<br/>
                Explanation: We can remove [5], [3,4], and [1,2] as strictly increasing subsequences. It requires 3 operations to empty the array.<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [1,2,3,4,5]<br/>
                Output: 1<br/>
                Explanation: We can remove the entire array [1,2,3,4,5] in one operation since it's strictly increasing.<br/><br/>
                Input: nums = [5,4,3,2,1]<br/>
                Output: 5<br/>
                Explanation: Each element must be removed separately since the array is strictly decreasing.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int minOperations(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        // Use a multiset to track the smallest tail of each increasing subsequence
        multiset&lt;int&gt; tails;
        
        for (int num : nums) {
            // Find the largest tail that is smaller than current number
            auto it = tails.lower_bound(num);
            
            if (it != tails.begin()) {
                // We can extend an existing subsequence
                --it;
                tails.erase(it);
            }
            
            // Add current number as a new tail
            tails.insert(num);
        }
        
        // The number of tails is the minimum number of operations needed
        return tails.size();
    }
};</code></pre>
